value.value: A region of sequence from the end of a BAC clone that may provide a highly specific marker.

definition.value: Requested by Keith Boroevich December, 2006.

value.value: Cytosolic 16S rRNA is an RNA component of the small subunit of cytosolic ribosomes in prokaryotes.

definition.value: Renamed to cytosolic_16S_rRNA from rRNA_16S on 10 June 2021 as per restructuring of rRNA child terms. Updated definition to be consistent with format of other rRNA definitions. Request from EBI. See GitHub Issue #493.

value.value: Cytosolic 23S rRNA is an RNA component of the large subunit of cytosolic ribosomes in prokaryotes.

definition.value: Renamed from rRNA_23S to cytosolic_23S_rRNA on 27 May 2021 with the restructuring of rRNA child terms. Updated definition to be consistent with format of other rRNA definitions. Requested by EBI. See GitHub Issue #493.

value.value: Cytosolic 25S rRNA is an RNA component of the large subunit of cytosolic ribosomes most eukaryotes.

definition.value: Renamed from rRNA_5S to cytosolic_5S_rRNA on 27 May 2021 with the restructuring of rRNA child terms. Updated definition to be consistent with format of other rRNA definitions. Requested by EBI. See GitHub Issue #493.

value.value: A recombination product between the 2 LTR of the same element.

definition.value: Requested by Hadi Quesneville January 2007.
When a sequence does not contain an equal distribution of all four possible nucleotide bases or does not contain all nucleotide bases.
A region where the DNA does not contain an equal distrubution of all four possible nucleotides or does not contain all four nucleotides.

value.value: A phage genome after it has established in the host genome in a latent/immune state either as a plasmid or as an integrated "island".
A remnant of an integrated prophage in the host genome or an "island" in the host genome that includes phage like-genes.

definition.value: This is not cryptic in the same sense as a cryptic gene or cryptic splice site.

value.value: A base-paired stem with loop of 4 non-hydrogen bonded nucleotides.
A double-stranded DNA used to control macromolecular structure and function.
A cytosine rich domain whereby strands associate both inter- and intramolecularly at moderately acidic pH.

Peptide nucleic acid, is a chemical not known to occur naturally but is artificially synthesized and used in some biological research and medical treatments. The PNA backbone is composed of repeating N-(2-aminoethyl)-glycine units linked by peptide bonds. The purine and pyrimidine bases are linked to the backbone by methylene carbonyl bonds.
A DNA sequence with catalytic activity.

definition.value: Added by request from Colin Batchelor.

value.value: A multiple nucleotide polymorphism with alleles of common length > 1, for example AAA/TTT.

definition.value: An intronic region that has an attribute.
Requested by Colin Batchelor, Feb 2007.

value.value: A type of non-canonical base pairing, most commonly between G and U, which is important for the secondary structure of RNAs. It has similar thermodynamic stability to the Watson-Crick pairing. Wobble base pairs only have two hydrogen bonds. Other wobble base pair possibilities are I-A, I-U and I-C.
A purine-rich sequence in the group I introns which determines the locations of the splice sites in group I intron splicing and has catalytic activity.

A sequence variant that does not affect protein function. Silent mutations may occur in genic ( CDS, UTR, intron etc) and intergenic regions. Silent mutations may have affects on processes such as splicing and regulation.

definition.value: Added in March 2007 in after meeting with PharmGKB. Although this term is in common usage, it is better to annotate with the most specific term possible, such as synonymous codon, intron variant etc.

value.value: A binding site that, in the molecule, interacts selectively and non-covalently with antibodies, B cells or T cells.

definition.value: Requested by Trish Whetzel.

value.value: A variation that increases or decreases the copy number of a given region.

definition.value: A chromosomal region that may sustain a double-strand break, resulting in a recombination event.

value.value: The point within a chromosome where an inversion begins or ends.
An allele is one of a set of coexisting sequence variants of a gene.
A haplotype is one of a set of coexisting sequence variants of a haplotype block.
A sequence variant that is segregating in one or more natural populations of a species.
A genome is the sum of genetic material within a cell or virion.
A genotype is a variant genome, complete or incomplete.
A diplotype is a pair of haplotypes from a given individual. It is a genotype where the phase is known.

definition.value: The attribute of whether the sequence is the same direction as a feature (forward) or the opposite direction as a feature (reverse).

value.value: Forward is an attribute of the feature, where the feature is in the 5' to 3' direction.
Reverse is an attribute of the feature, where the feature is in the 3' to 5' direction. Again could be applied to primer.

definition.value: DNA belonging to the genome of a mitochondria.
This terms is used by MO.
DNA belonging to the genome of a chloroplast, a photosynthetic plastid.
This term is used by MO.

value.value: A de-branched intron which mimics the structure of pre-miRNA and enters the miRNA processing pathway without Drosha mediated cleavage.

definition.value: Ruby et al. Nature 448:83 describe a new class of miRNAs that are derived from de-branched introns.

value.value: A small non coding RNA, part of a silencing system that prevents the spreading of selfish genetic elements.
A tRNA sequence that has an arginine anticodon, and a 3' arginine binding region.
A nucleotide region with either intra-genome or intracellular mobility, of varying length, which often carry the information necessary for transfer and recombination with the host genome.
An MGE that is not integrated into the host chromosome.
An MGE that is integrated into the host chromosome.
A plasmid sequence that is integrated within the host chromosome.
The region of nucleotide sequence of a virus, a submicroscopic particle that replicates by infecting a host cell.

definition.value: The definitions of the children of this term were revised Decemeber 2007 after discussion on song-devel. The resulting definitions are slightly unweildy but hopefully more logically correct.

value.value: The nucleotide sequence of a virus that infects bacteria.
An attachment site located on a conjugative transposon and used for site-specific integration of a conjugative transposon.
A nuclear pseudogene of either coding or non-coding mitochondria derived sequence.

definition.value: Definition change requested by Val, 3172757.

value.value: A MGE region consisting of two fused plasmids resulting from a replicative transposition event.
Component of the inversion site located at the left of a region susceptible to site-specific inversion.
Component of the inversion site located at the right of a region susceptible to site-specific inversion.
A region located within an inversion site.

definition.value: A term created to allow the parts of an inversion site have an is_a path back to the root.

value.value: An island that contains genes for integration/excision and the gene and site for the initiation of intercellular transfer by conjugation. It can be complemented for transfer by a conjugative transposon.
